{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6fd9785a-0e1e-469c-88c2-fa3d964714d8","content":"\n\nUse `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why:** `[ExpectedException]` can't verify *which line* threw, so a bug elsewhere in the test could silently pass. `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call and also returns the exception if you need to assert on its message or properties.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d38aa484-20b7-4738-aae8-5ec2e0f2cba8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a straightforward knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":221},"id":"9f398409-c592-4ae4-9eca-947790611561","timestamp":"2026-04-03T03:15:47.227Z","parentId":"7462ba04-9730-44f2-887f-bd1d6561ba63"}
